# Brachialis

> The **brachialis** is the primary **elbow flexor**, lying deep to the [[Biceps Brachii]] on the anterior humerus. Unlike the biceps, it inserts on the ulna (not the radius) and works regardless of forearm rotation.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Origin** — Anterior distal half of [[Humerus]] (below deltoid tuberosity)
- **Insertion** — [[Coronoid Process]] and ulnar tuberosity of [[Ulna]]
- **Nerve** — [[Musculocutaneous Nerve]] (C5, C6); small lateral slip by [[Radial Nerve]]
- **Action** — Elbow flexion (in all positions — pronated, supinated, neutral)

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Pure elbow flexor** — Works in all forearm positions (unlike biceps which supinates)
- **Anterior interosseous nerve** — Not related, but brachialis is a landmark for AIN branches
- **Brachialis strain** — "Climber's elbow" from repeated heavy elbow flexion

